    "projects": [
        {
            "title": "Curating An Exhibition In The Posthuman Context:  Augmented Reality, Cyborg Visions, & Digital Folklore",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 12,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 1,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2018
                }
            },
            "description": "This project took place as a 13-minute tripartite screencasting exhibition in Parnassos Cultural Centre, Utrecht (NL), consisting of three different topics and three different aesthetics. The first part which focused on augmented reality was a collage of augmented reality exhibitions, commenting the cultural change of what dimensions can have a painting, a performance or a piece of art in general. The second part focused on the ways that artists and scholars envision the posthuman, was a pluralistic frame of overlapping video lectures, video art, art-work pictures and texts which were all referring to that posthuman visions. Finally, the third part focused on the aesthetics of net art and its emergence from \u2018digital folklore\u2019.\nThrough our curatorial process, we tried to create a performative digital space which is not defined by its geographical coordinates or its temporal character, but rather by being a \u2018space of flows\u2019 in \u2018timeless time\u2019 (Castells, 2005). Our curatorial process was additionally inherently reflexive due to cyberspace\u2019s hypertextuality and hyperimmediacy, through which aesthetic objects are contextualized within a particular informational \u2018moment\u2019 in cyberspace. We attempted to showcase not only the artworks we collected, but also the curatorial process that occurs within cyberspace. ",
